data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` + fixture class |

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();       // OneTimeSetUp
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();          // OneTimeTearDown
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture _)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();           // SetUp
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();                       // TearDown
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Per-test setup** → constructor (xUnit creates a new instance per test)
- **Per-test teardown** → `IDisposable.Dispose()`
- **One-time setup/teardown** → extract to a fixture class; reference it via `IClassFixture<T>`. The fixture is created once and shared across all tests in the class.
- If you need the fixture instance (e.g., a shared connection), use the constructor parameter instead of discarding it with `_`.
